  "prompt": "What determines the specific heat of a substance?",
  "response": "The specific heat of a substance is determined by several factors:\n\n1. Atomic and Molecular Structure\n- Number of atoms in the molecule\n- Complexity of molecular bonds\n- Intermolecular forces\n- Degree of freedom for molecular movement\n\n2. Chemical Composition\n- Type of elements present\n- Arrangement of atoms\n- Molecular configuration\n\n3. Physical State\n- Solid, liquid, or gas\n- Molecular density\n- Atomic/molecular mobility\n\n4. Temperature\n- Specific heat can vary slightly with temperature\n- Changes in molecular vibration and energy levels\n\n5. Bonding Characteristics\n- Strength of chemical bonds\n- Types of chemical bonds (ionic, covalent, metallic)\n- Energy required to change molecular motion\n\n6. Quantum Mechanical Properties\n- Energy levels of electrons\n- Quantum interactions between atoms/molecules\n\n7. Pressure\n- Can influence molecular spacing\n- Affects intermolecular interactions\n\n8. Structural Complexity\n- More complex molecules generally have higher specific heat\n- More ways to store and transfer thermal energy\n\nThese factors collectively influence how much thermal energy a substance can absorb or release per unit mass for a given temperature change.",
